summarization.results: The diaconate originated from the Acts of the Apostles, with deacons serving as assistants to bishops in the early church. They were responsible for caring for the needy, maintaining order during liturgies, and ensuring charity work. Over time, the role of deacons evolved, with a distinction between transitional and permanent deacons. Vatican II restored the permanent diaconate to address the shortage of clergy, allowing married men to serve as deacons. Deaconesses existed in the early church to assist in baptizing women but did not have a role in liturgy.
